{"add":{"doc":{"id":"175c4b90ee093e01b9feffd8710e289e331d1f8be5bfd91a2ff634d29d8bc23f","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Symptoms_of_acute_HIV_infection.svg/275px-Symptoms_of_acute_HIV_infection.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["The initial period following the contraction of HIV is called acute HIV, primary HIV or acute retroviral syndrome.[14][16] Many individuals develop an influenza-like illness or a mononucleosis-like illness 2–4 weeks post exposure while others have no significant symptoms.[17][18] Symptoms occur in 40–90% of cases and most commonly include fever, large tender lymph nodes, throat inflammation, a rash, headache, and/or sores of the mouth and genitals.[16][18] The rash, which occurs in 20–50% of cases, presents itself on the trunk and is maculopapular, classically.[19] Some people also develop opportunistic infections at this stage.[16] Gastrointestinal symptoms such as nausea, vomiting or diarrhea may occur, as may neurological symptoms of peripheral neuropathy or Guillain-Barre syndrome.[18] The duration of the symptoms varies, but is usually one or two weeks.[18]"]}}}